[31m-The **BGA Start Sector** is a start method used in gliding competitions, particularly in the United Kingdom and other countries following British Gliding Association (BGA) rules. It provides a standardized way for gliders to begin racing tasks while ensuring fair and safe starts.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## What is a BGA Start Sector?[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### Definition[m
[31m-A BGA Start Sector is a **90-degree sector** positioned at the start point of a racing task. The sector opens **forward** in the direction of the first turnpoint, creating a "slice of pie" shaped area from which pilots must begin their racing task.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### Key Characteristics[m
[31m-- **Shape**: 90-degree sector (quarter circle)[m
[31m-- **Orientation**: Opens toward the first turnpoint[m
[31m-- **Size**: Typically 1-5km radius (configurable based on task requirements)[m
[31m-- **Entry**: Pilots must be **inside** the sector to achieve a valid start[m
[31m-- **Direction**: Forward-facing (bisector aligned with track to first turnpoint)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Visual Representation[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-                First Turnpoint[m
[31m-                      *'[m
[31m-                     /|\[m
[31m-                    / | \[m
[31m-                   /  |  \[m
[31m-                  /   |   \ * 45deg each side of bisector[m
[31m-                 /    |    \[m
[31m-                /     |     \[m
[31m-               /_____[S]_____\ * Start point at sector vertex[m
[31m-              *"""" 1-5km """"*'[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## How BGA Start Sectors Work[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### 1. **Sector Positioning**[m
[31m-- **Vertex**: Located exactly at the start waypoint coordinates[m
[31m-- **Bisector**: Aligned with the bearing from start point to first turnpoint[m
[31m-- **Opening**: 45 degrees either side of the bisector (total 90deg)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### 2. **Start Procedure**[m
[31m-1. **Pre-Start**: Pilots position themselves **inside** the start sector[m
[31m-2. **Start Signal**: At the designated start time, pilots may begin racing[m
[31m-3. **Valid Start**: Pilot must be inside the sector when crossing the start time[m
[31m-4. **Exit**: Pilots proceed toward the first turnpoint[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### 3. **Entry Rules**[m
[31m-- Pilots may enter the sector from **any direction**[m
[31m-- Most commonly enter from **behind** (opposite to task direction)[m
[31m-- Must be **fully inside** the sector boundaries for valid start[m
[31m-- Can maneuver within the sector while waiting for start time[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Advantages of BGA Start Sectors[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Tactical Benefits**[m
[31m-- **Positioning Freedom**: Pilots can choose optimal position within the sector[m
[31m-- **Wind Consideration**: Can position according to wind direction and thermals[m
[31m-- **Traffic Management**: 90deg spread reduces congestion compared to start lines[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Safety Benefits**[m
[31m-- **Defined Area**: Clear boundaries reduce confusion about valid start positions[m
[31m-- **Spacing**: Natural pilot distribution across the sector width[m
[31m-- **Forward Orientation**: Encourages organized departure toward first turnpoint[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Operational Benefits**[m
[31m-- **Easy to Define**: Simply specify radius and let system calculate orientation[m
[31m-- **GPS Compatible**: Modern flight computers can easily detect sector boundaries[m
[31m-- **Flexible Sizing**: Radius can be adjusted based on expected field size[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Comparison with Other Start Methods[m
[31m-[m
[31m-| Start Method | Shape | Advantages | Disadvantages |[m
[31m-|--------------|-------|------------|---------------|[m
[31m-| **BGA Start Sector** | 90deg sector | Good positioning freedom, forward-facing | Requires understanding of sector boundaries |[m
[31m-| **Start Line** | Straight line | Simple to understand, traditional | Can create congestion, perpendicular to track |[m
[31m-| **Start Cylinder** | Full circle | Maximum positioning freedom | Can encourage late starts, no directional guidance |[m
[31m-| **FAI Start Quadrant** | 90deg sector (infinite) | Large area, competition standard | Complex orientation rules, visual radius needed |[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Technical Implementation[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Calculation Requirements**[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-Bisector Bearing = bearing(start_point *' first_turnpoint)[m
[31m-Start Angle = (Bisector - 45deg) mod 360deg[m
[31m-End Angle = (Bisector + 45deg) mod 360deg[m
[31m-Sector Radius = configurable (typically 1-5km)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Validation Logic**[m
[31m-For a position to be valid within a BGA start sector:[m
[31m-1. **Distance Check**: `distance_to_start per-mille$ sector_radius`[m
[31m-2. **Angle Check**: `position_bearing` within `[start_angle, end_angle]`[m
[31m-3. **Both conditions** must be satisfied[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Visual Rendering**[m
[31m-- **Polygon**: Arc from start_angle to end_angle + radial lines back to center[m
[31m-- **Fill**: Semi-transparent to show underlying map features[m
[31m-- **Border**: Solid line to clearly define boundaries[m
[31m-- **Label**: "START" or sector identification[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Usage in Different Competition Classes[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Club Racing**[m
[31m-- **Radius**: Typically 1-2km[m
[31m-- **Purpose**: Local competitions with smaller fields[m
[31m-- **Considerations**: Shorter tasks, less crowded starts[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Regional Competitions**[m
[31m-- **Radius**: Typically 2-3km[m
[31m-- **Purpose**: Larger fields, longer tasks[m
[31m-- **Considerations**: More strategic positioning required[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **National/International**[m
[31m-- **Radius**: Up to 5km[m
[31m-- **Purpose**: Large competitive fields[m
[31m-- **Considerations**: Maximum tactical advantage for elite pilots[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Pilot Strategy Considerations[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Positioning Within Sector**[m
[31m-- **Wind Side**: Position upwind within sector for better climb access[m
[31m-- **Thermal Location**: Near known thermal sources if available[m
[31m-- **Traffic**: Avoid crowded areas, plan exit route[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Start Timing**[m
[31m-- **Early Start**: Risk of starting in poor conditions[m
[31m-- **Late Start**: May miss optimal conditions but can observe others[m
[31m-- **Tactical Start**: Balance between conditions and competitive position[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### **Exit Strategy**[m
[31m-- **Direct Route**: Straight toward first turnpoint[m
[31m-- **Tactical Route**: Deviate for better lift or wind conditions[m
[31m-- **Traffic Management**: Avoid conflicts with other gliders[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Common Misconceptions[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### oe **"BGA sectors are the same as FAI quadrants"**[m
[31m-- **BGA**: 90deg sector with **finite radius**[m
[31m-- **FAI**: 90deg sector with **infinite radius** and complex orientation rules[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### oe **"The sector opens backward"**[m
[31m-- **Correct**: BGA sectors open **forward** toward the first turnpoint[m
[31m-- **Logic**: Encourages organized departure in task direction[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### oe **"Any position near the start point is valid"**[m
[31m-- **Correct**: Must be **inside both** radius and angle boundaries[m
[31m-- **Validation**: Both distance and bearing criteria must be met[m
